[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] CIL was originally known as Microsoft Intermediate Language (MSIL) during the beta releases of the .NET languages.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Due to standardization of C# and the CLI, the bytecode is now officially known as CIL.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Windows Defender virus definitions continue to refer to binaries compiled with it as MSIL.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] During compilation of CLI programming languages, the source code is translated into CIL code rather than into platform- or processor-specific object code.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] CIL is a CPU- and platform-independent instruction set that can be executed in any environment supporting the Common Language Infrastructure, such as the .NET runtime on Windows, or the cross-platform Mono runtime.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] In theory, this eliminates the need to distribute different executable files for different platforms and CPU types.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] CIL code is verified for safety during runtime, providing better security and reliability than natively compiled executable files.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Upon execution of a CIL assembly, its code is passed through the runtime's JIT compiler to generate native code.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Ahead-of-time compilation may also be used, which eliminates this step, but at the cost of executable-file portability.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The computer's processor executes the native code.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The Common Intermediate Language is object-oriented and stack-based, which means that instruction parameters and results are kept on a single stack instead of in several registers or other memory locations, as in most programming languages.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] In the latter example, the values of the two registers, eax and edx, are first pushed on the stack.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] When the add-instruction is called the operands are "popped", or retrieved, and the result is "pushed", or stored, on the stack.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The resulting value is then popped from the stack and stored in eax.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] One may create objects, call methods, and use other types of members, such as fields.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Every method needs (with some exceptions) to reside in a class.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] An instance class contains at least one constructor and some instance members.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The following class has a set of methods representing actions of a Car-object.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) records information about compiled classes as metadata.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Like the type library in the Component Object Model, this enables applications to support and discover the interfaces, classes, types, methods, and fields in the assembly.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The process of reading such metadata is called "reflection".
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Metadata can be data in the form of "attributes".
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Attributes can be customized by extending the `Attribute` class.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] It allows the creator of the class the ability to adorn it with extra information that consumers of the class can use in various meaningful ways, depending on the application domain.
