[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] This makes CIL a very easy target for reverse engineering.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] This trait is shared with Java bytecode.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] However, there are tools that can obfuscate the code, and do it so that the code cannot be easily readable but still be runnable.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] Just-in-time compilation (JIT) involves turning the byte-code into code immediately executable by the CPU.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] The conversion is performed gradually during the program's execution.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] JIT compilation provides environment-specific optimization and assembly verification.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] To accomplish this, the JIT compiler examines the assembly metadata for any illegal accesses and handles violations appropriately.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] CLI-compatible execution environments also come with the option to do an Ahead-of-time compilation (AOT) of an assembly to make it execute faster by removing the JIT process at runtime.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] In the .NET Framework there is a special tool called the Native Image Generator (NGEN) that performs the AOT.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] A different approach for AOT is CoreRT that allows the compilation of .Net Core code to a single executable with no dependency on a runtime.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-intermediate-language] A notable difference from Java's bytecode is that CIL comes with `ldind`, `stind`, `ldloca`, and many call instructions which are enough for data/function pointers manipulation needed to compile C/C++ code into CIL.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] The **Common Language Runtime** (**CLR**), the virtual machine component of Microsoft .NET Framework, manages the execution of .NET programs.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] Just-in-time compilation converts the managed code (compiled intermediate language code) into machine instructions which are then executed on the CPU of the computer.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] The CLR provides additional services including memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] All programs written for the .NET Framework, regardless of programming language, are executed in the CLR.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] All versions of the .NET Framework include CLR.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] CLR implements the Virtual Execution System (VES) as defined in the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) standard, initially developed by Microsoft itself.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] A public standard defines the Common Language Infrastructure specification.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-language-runtime] During the transition from legacy .NET technologies like the .NET Framework and its proprietary runtime to the community-developed .NET Core, the CLR was dubbed **CoreCLR**.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] In Microsoft's .NET Framework, the **Common Type System** (**CTS**) is a standard that specifies how type definitions and specific values of types are represented in computer memory.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] It is intended to allow programs written in different programming languages to easily share information.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] As used in programming languages, a type can be described as a definition of a set of values (for example, "all integers between 0 and 10"), and the allowable operations on those values (for example, addition and subtraction).
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] The specification for the CTS is contained in Ecma standard 335, "Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) Partitions I to VI." The CLI and the CTS were created by Microsoft, and the Microsoft .NET framework is an implementation of the standard.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] When rounding fractional values, the halfway-to-even ("banker's") method is used by default, throughout the Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] Since version 2, "Symmetric Arithmetic Rounding" (round halves away from zero) is also available by programmer's option.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] Value types can be built-in (implemented by the runtime), user-defined, or enumerations.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] Reference types can be self-describing types, pointer types, or interface types.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] The type of a reference type can be determined from values of self-describing types.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] Self-describing types are further split into arrays and class types.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] The class types are user-defined classes, boxed value types, and delegates.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] Converting value types to reference types is also known as boxing.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] As can be seen in the example below, it is not necessary to tell the compiler an Int32 is boxed to an object, because it takes care of this itself.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] The following example intends to show how to unbox a reference type back to a value type.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] First an Int32 is boxed to an object, and then it is unboxed again.
[src:dotnet-clr/common-type-system] Note that unboxing requires explicit cast.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] In computer science, **garbage collection** (**GC**) is a form of automatic memory management.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The *garbage collector* attempts to reclaim memory that was allocated by the program, but is no longer referenced; such memory is called *garbage*.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection was invented by American computer scientist John McCarthy around 1959 to simplify manual memory management in Lisp.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection relieves the programmer from doing manual memory management, where the programmer specifies what objects to de-allocate and return to the memory system and when to do so.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other, similar techniques include stack allocation, region inference, and memory ownership, and combinations thereof.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection may take a significant proportion of a program's total processing time, and affect performance as a result.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Resources other than memory, such as network sockets, database handles, windows, file descriptors, and device descriptors, are not typically handled by garbage collection, but rather by other methods (e.g. destructors).
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some such methods de-allocate memory also.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Many programming languages require garbage collection, either as part of the language specification (e.g., RPL, Java, C#, D, Go, and most scripting languages) or effectively for practical implementation (e.g., formal languages like lambda calculus).
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] These are said to be *garbage-collected languages*.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other languages, such as C and C++, were designed for use with manual memory management, but have garbage-collected implementations available.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some languages, like Ada, Modula-3, and C++/CLI, allow both garbage collection and manual memory management to co-exist in the same application by using separate heaps for collected and manually managed objects.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Still others, like D, are garbage-collected but allow the user to manually delete objects or even disable garbage collection entirely when speed is required.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although many languages integrate GC into their compiler and runtime system, *post-hoc* GC systems also exist, such as Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some of these *post-hoc* GC systems do not require recompilation.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC frees the programmer from manually de-allocating memory.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC uses computing resources to decide which memory to free.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Therefore, the penalty for the convenience of not annotating object lifetime manually in the source code is overhead, which can impair program performance.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] A peer-reviewed paper from 2005 concluded that GC needs five times the memory to compensate for this overhead and to perform as fast as the same program using idealized explicit memory management.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The comparison however is made to a program generated by inserting deallocation calls using an oracle, implemented by collecting traces from programs run under a profiler, and the program is only correct for one particular execution of the program.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Interaction with memory hierarchy effects can make this overhead intolerable in circumstances that are hard to predict or to detect in routine testing.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The impact on performance was given by Apple as a reason for not adopting garbage collection in iOS, despite it being the most desired feature.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The moment when the garbage is actually collected can be unpredictable, resulting in stalls (pauses to shift/free memory) scattered throughout a session.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unpredictable stalls can be unacceptable in real-time environments, in transaction processing, or in interactive programs.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors address these problems, with varying trade-offs.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Tracing garbage collection is the most common type of garbage collection, so much so that "garbage collection" often refers to tracing garbage collection, rather than other methods such as reference counting.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The overall strategy consists of determining which objects should be garbage collected by tracing which objects are *reachable* by a chain of references from certain root objects, and considering the rest as garbage and collecting them.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, there are a large number of algorithms used in implementation, with widely varying complexity and performance characteristics.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting garbage collection is where each object has a count of the number of references to it.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage is identified by having a reference count of zero.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] An object's reference count is incremented when a reference to it is created and decremented when a reference is destroyed.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] When the count reaches zero, the object's memory is reclaimed.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] If two or more objects refer to each other, they can create a cycle whereby neither will be collected as their mutual references never let their reference counts become zero.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] ) use specific cycle-detecting algorithms to deal with this issue.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] for the "backpointers" which create cycles.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Under reference counting, a weak reference is similar to a weak reference under a tracing garbage collector.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is a special reference object whose existence does not increment the reference count of the referent object.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] , rather than being permitted to remain dangling, meaning that it turns into a predictable value, such as a null reference.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting requires space to be allocated for each object to store its reference count.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The count may be stored adjacent to the object's memory or in a side table somewhere else, but in either case, every single reference-counted object requires additional storage for its reference count.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Memory space with the size of an unsigned pointer is commonly used for this task, meaning that 32 or 64 bits of reference count storage must be allocated for each object.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] to store the reference count in unused areas of the object's memory.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Often, an architecture does not actually allow programs to access the full range of memory addresses that could be stored in its native pointer size; a certain number of high bits in the address is either ignored or required to be zero.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] If an object reliably has a pointer at a certain location, the reference count can be stored in the unused bits of the pointer.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] , 19 unused bits of this class pointer are used to store the object's reference count.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] In naive implementations, each assignment of a reference and each reference falling out of scope often require modifications of one or more reference counters.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, in a common case when a reference is copied from an outer scope variable into an inner scope variable, such that the lifetime of the inner variable is bounded by the lifetime of the outer one, the reference incrementing can be eliminated.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The outer variable "owns" the reference.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] whose constructors, destructors, and assignment operators manage the references.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] A smart pointer can be passed by reference to a function, which avoids the need to copy-construct a new smart pointer (which would increase the reference count on entry into the function and decrease it on exit).
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Instead, the function receives a reference to the smart pointer which is produced inexpensively.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Deutsch-Bobrow method of reference counting capitalizes on the fact that most reference count updates are in fact generated by references stored in local variables.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] It ignores these references, only counting references in the heap, but before an object with reference count zero can be deleted, the system must verify with a scan of the stack and register that no other reference to it still exists.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Consider a pointer that in a given interval of the execution is updated several times.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] But most of these updates are redundant.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Levanoni and Petrank measured an elimination of more than 99% of the counter updates in typical Java benchmarks.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] , at least for any objects which are shared, or potentially shared among multiple threads.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Atomic operations are expensive on a multiprocessor, and even more expensive if they have to be emulated with software algorithms.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] can be used to eliminate all atomic operations from the write-barrier.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Counters are never updated by the program threads in the course of program execution.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] They are only modified by the collector which executes as a single additional thread with no synchronization.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] This method can be used as a stop-the-world mechanism for parallel programs, and also with a concurrent reference counting collector.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Naive implementations of reference counting do not generally provide real-time behavior, because any pointer assignment can potentially cause a number of objects bounded only by total allocated memory size to be recursively freed while the thread is unable to perform other work.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is possible to avoid this issue by delegating the freeing of unreferenced objects to other threads, at the cost of extra overhead.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Escape analysis is a compile-time technique that can convert heap allocations to stack allocations, thereby reducing the amount of garbage collection to be done.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] This analysis determines whether an object allocated inside a function is accessible outside of it.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] If a function-local allocation is found to be accessible to another function or thread, the allocation is said to "escape" and cannot be done on the stack.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Otherwise, the object may be allocated directly on the stack and released when the function returns, bypassing the heap and associated memory management costs.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generally speaking, higher-level programming languages are more likely to have garbage collection as a standard feature.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] In some languages lacking built-in garbage collection, it can be added through a library, as with the Boehm garbage collector for C and C++.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most functional programming languages, such as ML, Haskell, and APL, have garbage collection built in.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Lisp is especially notable as both the first functional programming language and the first language to introduce garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other dynamic languages, such as Ruby and Julia (but not Perl 5 or PHP before version 5.3, which both use reference counting), JavaScript and ECMAScript also tend to use GC.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Object-oriented programming languages such as Smalltalk, ooRexx, RPL and Java usually provide integrated garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Notable exceptions are C++ and Delphi, which have destructors.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC and Logo have often used garbage collection for variable-length data types, such as strings and lists, so as not to burden programmers with memory management details.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] On the Altair 8800, programs with many string variables and little string space could cause long pauses due to garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Similarly the Applesoft BASIC interpreter's garbage collection algorithm repeatedly scans the string descriptors for the string having the highest address in order to compact it toward high memory, resulting in $O(n^{2})$ performance and pauses anywhere from a few seconds to a few minutes.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] A replacement garbage collector for Applesoft BASIC by Randy Wigginton identifies a group of strings in every pass over the heap, reducing collection time dramatically.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC.SYSTEM, released with ProDOS in 1983, provides a windowing garbage collector for BASIC that is many times faster.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] C has never offered official support for garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] C++ added garbage collection support in C++11 to the standard library, however this was removed in C++23 due to no compilers implementing support for the feature.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The features that were part of this were related to pointer safety.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although garbage collection support in the standard library was removed, some garbage collectors such as Boehm garbage collector (for C and C++) can still be used.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Boehm GC uses mark-and-sweep garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] It can also be used in leak detection mode, where memory management is still manual however leaks and double-free errors can be detected and reported.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Its use can be called from the header `<gc.h>`.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] One can still abstract away manual object destructions in C++ by using the "resource acquisition is initialization" (RAII) idiom and smart pointers.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::unique_ptr` ties lifetimes to ownership, while `std::shared_ptr` uses reference counting to determine lifetime.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::weak_ptr` can be used to obtain a pointer without increasing the reference count.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unlike garbage collection, RAII is deterministic.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] While the Objective-C traditionally had no garbage collection, with the release of OS X 10.5 in 2007 Apple introduced garbage collection for Objective-C 2.0, using an in-house developed runtime collector.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, with the 2012 release of OS X 10.8, garbage collection was deprecated in favor of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) that was introduced with OS X 10.7.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Furthermore, since May 2015 Apple even forbade the usage of garbage collection for new OS X applications in the App Store.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] For iOS, garbage collection has never been introduced due to problems in application responsivity and performance; instead, iOS uses ARC.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection is rarely used on embedded or real-time systems because of the usual need for very tight control over the use of limited resources.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, garbage collectors compatible with many limited environments have been developed.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Microsoft .NET Micro Framework, .NET nanoFramework and Java Platform, Micro Edition are embedded software platforms that, like their larger cousins, include garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Compile-time garbage collection is a form of static analysis allowing memory to be reused and reclaimed based on invariants known during compilation.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] This form of garbage collection has been studied in the Mercury programming language, and it saw greater usage with the introduction of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) into Apple's ecosystem (iOS and OS X) in 2011.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors have been developed, for example by Henry Baker and by Henry Lieberman.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] In Baker's algorithm, the allocation is done in either half of a single region of memory.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] When it becomes half full, a garbage collection is performed which moves the live objects into the other half and the remaining objects are implicitly deallocated.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] The running program (the 'mutator') has to check that any object it references is in the correct half, and if not move it across, while a background task is finding all of the objects.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generational garbage collection schemes are based on the empirical observation that most objects die young.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] In generational garbage collection, two or more allocation regions (generations) are kept, which are kept separate based on the object's age.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] New objects are created in the "young" generation that is regularly collected, and when a generation is full, the objects that are still referenced from older regions are copied into the next oldest generation.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some high-level language computer architectures include hardware support for real-time garbage collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most implementations of real-time garbage collectors use tracing.
[src:dotnet-clr/garbage-collection-computer-science] Such real-time garbage collectors meet hard real-time constraints when used with a real-time operating system.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:dotnet-clr/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The **.NET Framework** (pronounced "*dot net*") is a proprietary software framework developed by Microsoft that runs primarily on Microsoft Windows.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It was the predominant implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) until being superseded by the cross-platform .NET project.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It includes a large class library called Framework Class Library (FCL) and provides language interoperability (each language can use code written in other languages) across several programming languages.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework execute in a software environment (in contrast to a hardware environment) named the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The CLR is an application virtual machine that provides services such as security, memory management, and exception handling.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] As such, computer code written using .NET Framework is called "managed code".
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] FCL and CLR together constitute the .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] FCL provides the user interface, data access, database connectivity, cryptography, web application development, numeric algorithms, and network communications.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Programmers produce software by combining their source code with the .NET Framework and other libraries.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The framework is intended to be used by most new applications created for the Windows platform.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft also produces an integrated development environment for .NET software called Visual Studio.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework began as proprietary software, although the firm worked to standardize the software stack almost immediately, even before its first release.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Despite the standardization efforts, developers, mainly those in the free and open-source software communities, expressed their unease with the selected terms and the prospects of any free and open-source implementation, especially regarding software patents.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Since then, Microsoft has changed .NET development to more closely follow a contemporary model of a community-developed software project, including issuing an update to its patent promising to address the concerns.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] In April 2019, Microsoft released .NET Framework 4.8, the last major version of the framework as a proprietary offering, followed by .NET Framework 4.8.1 in August 2022.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Only monthly security and reliability bug fixes to that version have been released since then.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] No further changes to that version are planned.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The .NET Framework will continue to be included with future releases of Windows and continue to receive security updates, with no plans to remove it as of July 2025.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft began developing .NET Framework in the late 1990s, originally under the name of Next Generation Windows Services (NGWS), as part of the Microsoft .NET strategy.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] By early 2000, the first beta versions of .NET 1.0 were released.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] In August 2000, Microsoft and Intel worked to standardize Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) and C#.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] By December 2001, both were ratified as ECMA standards.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] International Organization for Standardization (ISO) followed in April 2003.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The current version of ISO standards are ISO/IEC 23271:2012 and ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] While Microsoft and their partners hold patents for CLI and C#, ECMA and ISO require that all patents essential to implementation be made available under "reasonable and non-discriminatory terms".
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The firms agreed to meet these terms, and to make the patents available royalty-free.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] However, this did not apply to the part of the .NET Framework not covered by ECMA-ISO standards, which included Windows Forms, ADO.NET, and ASP.NET.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Patents that Microsoft holds in these areas may have deterred non-Microsoft implementations of the full framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Windows Vista is the first client version of Windows that integrated the .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] On October 3, 2007, Microsoft announced that the source code for .NET Framework 3.5 libraries was to become available under the Microsoft Reference Source License (Ms-RSL).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The source code repository became available online on January 16, 2008, and included BCL, ASP.NET, ADO.NET, Windows Forms, WPF, and XML.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Scott Guthrie of Microsoft promised that LINQ, WCF, and WF libraries were being added.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The .NET Compact Framework and .NET Micro Framework variants of the .NET Framework provided support for other Microsoft platforms such as Windows Mobile, Windows CE and other resource-constrained embedded devices.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Silverlight provided support for web browsers via plug-ins.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] In November 2014, Microsoft also produced an update to its patent grants, which further extends the scope beyond its prior pledges.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Prior projects like Mono existed in a legal gray area because Microsoft's earlier grants applied only to the technology in "covered specifications", including strictly the 4th editions each of ECMA-334 and ECMA-335.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The new patent promise, however, places no ceiling on the specification version, and even extends to any .NET runtime technologies documented on MSDN that have not been formally specified by the ECMA group, if a project chooses to implement them.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] This allows Mono and other projects to maintain feature parity with modern .NET features that have been introduced since the 4th edition was published all without being at risk of patent litigation over the implementation of those features.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The new grant does maintain the restriction that any implementation must maintain minimum compliance with the mandatory parts of the CLI specification.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] On March 31, 2016, Microsoft announced at Microsoft Build that they will completely relicense Mono under an MIT License even in scenarios where formerly a commercial license was needed.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft also supplemented its prior patent promise for Mono, stating that they will not assert any "applicable patents" against parties that are "using, selling, offering for sale, importing, or distributing Mono." It was announced that the Mono Project was contributed to the .NET Foundation.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] These developments followed the acquisition of Xamarin, which began in February 2016 and was finished on March 18, 2016.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft's press release highlights that the cross-platform commitment now allows for a fully open-source, modern server-side .NET stack.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft released the source code for WPF, Windows Forms and WinUI on December 4, 2018.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) provides a language-neutral platform for application development and execution.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] By implementing the core aspects of .NET Framework within the scope of CLI, these functions will not be tied to one language but will be available across the many languages supported by the framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework includes the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It serves as the execution engine of .NET Framework and offers many services such as memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] All programs written for .NET Framework are executed by the CLR.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework are compiled into Common Intermediate Language code (CIL), as opposed to being directly compiled into machine code.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] During execution, an architecture-specific just-in-time compiler (JIT) turns the CIL code into machine code.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Compiled CLI code is stored in CLI assemblies.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] As mandated by the specification, assemblies are stored in Portable Executable (PE) file format, common on Windows platform for all *dynamic-link library* (DLL) and *executable* EXE files.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Each assembly consists of one or more files, one of which must contain a manifest bearing the metadata for the assembly.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The complete name of an assembly (not to be confused with the file name on disk) contains its simple text name, version number, culture, and public key token.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Assemblies are considered equivalent if they share the same complete name.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] A private key can also be used by the creator of the assembly for strong naming.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The public key token determines the real-world identity of the assembly's signer.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Only those knowing their private key (of the double-key cryptography system) can sign assemblies that have the same strong name as a prior version assembly.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Strong naming is required to add assemblies to Global Assembly Cache.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Starting with Visual Studio 2015, .NET Native compilation technology allows for the compilation of .NET code of Universal Windows Platform apps directly to machine code rather than CIL code, but the app must be written in either C# or Visual Basic.NET.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework includes an implementation of the CLI foundational Standard Libraries.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The .NET Framework Class Library (FCL) is organized in a hierarchy of namespaces.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Most of the built-in application programming interfaces (APIs) are part of either `System.*` or `Microsoft.*` namespaces.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] These class libraries implement many common functions, such as file reading and writing, graphic rendering, database interaction, and XML document manipulation.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The class libraries are available for all CLI compliant languages.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The FCL implements the CLI Base Class Library (BCL) and other class libraries—some are specified by CLI and others are Microsoft specific.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] BCL includes a small subset of the entire class library and is the core set of classes that serve as the basic API of CLR.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] For .NET Framework most classes considered being part of BCL reside in `mscorlib.dll`, `System.dll` and `System.Core.dll`.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] BCL classes are available in .NET Framework as well as in CLI's alternative implementations, including .NET Compact Framework, Microsoft Silverlight, .NET Core and Mono.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] FCL refers to the entire class library that ships with .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It includes BCL, an expanded set of libraries, including Windows Forms, ASP.NET, and Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), and also extensions to the base class libraries ADO.NET, Language Integrated Query (LINQ), Windows Communication Foundation (WCF), and Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] FCL is much larger in scope than standard libraries for languages like C++, and comparable in scope to standard libraries of Java.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] With the introduction of alternative CLI's implementations (e.g., Silverlight), Microsoft introduced the concept of Portable Class Libraries (PCL) allowing a consuming library to run on more than one implementation.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] With the further proliferation of implementations, the PCL approach failed to scale (PCLs are defined intersections of API surface between two or more implementations).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] As the next evolutionary step of PCL, the .NET Standard Library was created retroactively based on the `System.Runtime.dll` based APIs found in UWP and Silverlight.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] New CLI's implementations are encouraged to implement a version of the Standard Library allowing them to run existent third-party libraries with no need of creating new versions of them.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The .NET Standard Library allows an independent evolution of the library and app model layers within the .NET architecture.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] NuGet is the package manager for all .NET platforms.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It is used to retrieve third-party libraries into a .NET project with a global library feed at NuGet.org.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Private feeds can be maintained separately, e.g., by a build server or a file system directory.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft introduced C++/CLI in Visual Studio 2005, which is a language and means of compiling Visual C++ programs to run within the .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Some parts of the C++ program still run within an unmanaged Visual C++ Runtime, while specially modified parts are translated into CIL code and run with the .NET Framework's CLR.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Assemblies compiled using the C++/CLI compiler are termed mixed-mode assemblies since they contain native and managed code in the same DLL.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Such assemblies are more complex to reverse engineer since .NET decompilers such as .NET Reflector reveal only the managed code.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Because computer systems commonly require interaction between newer and older applications, .NET Framework provides means to access functions implemented in newer and older programs that execute outside .NET environment.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Access to Component Object Model (COM) components is provided in `System.Runtime.InteropServices` and `System.EnterpriseServices` namespaces of the framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Access to other functions is via Platform Invocation Services (P/Invoke).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Access to .NET functions from native applications is via the reverse P/Invoke function.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework introduces a Common Type System (CTS) that defines all possible data types and programming constructs supported by CLR and how they may or may not interact conforming to CLI specifications.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Because of this feature, .NET Framework supports the exchange of types and object instances between libraries and applications written using any conforming CLI language.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] CTS and the CLR used in .NET Framework also enforce type safety.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] This prevents ill-defined casts, wrong method invocations, and memory size issues when accessing an object.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] This also makes most CLI languages statically typed (with or without type inference).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] However, starting with .NET Framework 4.0, the Dynamic Language Runtime extended the CLR, allowing dynamically typed languages to be implemented atop the CLI.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] While Microsoft has never implemented the full framework on any system except Microsoft Windows, it has engineered the framework to be cross-platform, and implementations are available for other operating systems (see Silverlight and § Alternative implementations).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Microsoft submitted the specifications for CLI (which includes the Base Class Libraries, CTS, and CIL), C#, and C++/CLI to both Ecma International (ECMA) and International Organization for Standardization (ISO), making them available as official standards.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] This makes it possible for third parties to create compatible implementations of the framework and its languages on other platforms.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Core cross-platform .NET (formerly .NET Core) is officially available also for many Linux distributions and macOS.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework has its own security mechanism with two general features: Code Access Security (CAS), and validation and verification.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] CAS is based on evidence that is associated with a specific assembly.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Typically, the evidence is the source of the assembly (whether it is installed on the local machine or has been downloaded from the Internet).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] CAS uses evidence to determine the permissions granted to the code.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] When calling code demands that it be granted a specific permission, CLR performs a call stack walk checking every assembly of each method in the call stack for the required permission; if any assembly is not granted the permission, it will throw a security exception.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Managed CIL bytecode is easier to reverse-engineer than native code, unless obfuscated. .NET decompiler programs enable developers with no reverse-engineering skills to view the source code behind unobfuscated .NET assemblies.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] In contrast, apps compiled from native machine code are much harder to reverse-engineer, and source code is almost never produced successfully, mainly because of compiler optimizations and lack of reflection.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] This creates concerns in the business community over the possible loss of trade secrets and the bypassing of license control mechanisms.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] To mitigate this, Microsoft has included Dotfuscator Community Edition with Visual Studio .NET since 2002.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Third-party obfuscation tools are also available from vendors such as VMware, V.i.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Method-level encryption tools for .NET code are available from vendors such as SafeNet.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] CLR frees the developer from the burden of managing memory (allocating and freeing up when done); it handles memory management itself by detecting when memory can be safely freed.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Instantiations of .NET types (objects) are allocated from the managed heap; a pool of memory managed by CLR.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] As long as a reference to an object exists, which may be either direct, or via a graph of objects, the object is considered to be in use.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] When no reference to an object exists, and it cannot be reached or used, it becomes garbage, eligible for collection.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework includes a garbage collector (GC) which runs periodically, on a separate thread from the application's thread, that enumerates all the unusable objects and reclaims the memory allocated to them.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It is a non-deterministic, compacting, mark-and-sweep garbage collector.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] GC runs only when a set amount of memory has been used or there is enough pressure for memory on the system.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Since it is not guaranteed when the conditions to reclaim memory are reached, GC runs are non-deterministic.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Each .NET application has a set of roots, which are pointers to objects on the managed heap (*managed objects*).
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] These include references to static objects, objects defined as local variables or method parameters currently in scope, and objects referred to by CPU registers.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] When GC runs, it pauses the application and then, for each object referred to in the root, it recursively enumerates all the objects reachable from the root objects and marks them as reachable.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It uses CLI metadata and reflection to discover the objects encapsulated by an object, and then recursively walk them.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] It then enumerates all the objects on the heap (which were initially allocated contiguously) using reflection.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] All objects not marked as reachable are garbage.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Since the memory held by garbage is of no consequence, it is considered free space.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] However, this leaves chunks of free space between objects which were initially contiguous.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The objects are then *compacted* together to make free space on the managed heap contiguous again.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Any reference to an object invalidated by moving the object is updated by GC to reflect the new location.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The application is resumed after garbage collection ends.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The latest version of .NET framework uses concurrent garbage collection along with user code, making pauses unnoticeable, because it is done in the background.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The garbage collector used by .NET Framework is also *generational*.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Newly created objects are tagged *Generation 0*.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Objects that survive one garbage collection are tagged *Generation 1*.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Generation 1 objects that survive another collection are *Generation 2*.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The framework uses up to Generation 2 objects.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Higher generation objects are garbage collected less often than lower generation objects.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] This raises the efficiency of garbage collection, as older objects tend to have longer lifetimes than newer objects.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] By ignoring older objects in most collection runs, fewer checks and compaction operations are needed in total.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] When an application is first launched, the .NET Framework compiles the CIL code into executable code using its just-in-time compiler, and caches the executable program into the .NET Native Image Cache.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Due to caching, the application launches faster for subsequent launches, although the first launch is usually slower.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] To speed up the first launch, developers may use the Native Image Generator utility to manually ahead-of-time compile and cache any .NET application.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] The garbage collector, which is integrated into the environment, can introduce unanticipated delays of execution over which the developer has little direct control.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework provides support for calling Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) via managed code from April 2014 in Visual Studio 2013 Update 2.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] However, Mono has provided support for SIMD Extensions as of version 2.2 within the Mono.Simd namespace in 2009.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Mono's lead developer Miguel de Icaza has expressed hope that this SIMD support will be adopted by CLR's ECMA standard.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Streaming SIMD Extensions have been available in x86 CPUs since the introduction of the Pentium III.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Some other architectures such as ARM and MIPS also have SIMD extensions.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] In case the CPU lacks support for those extensions, the instructions are simulated in software.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] .NET Framework was the predominant implementation of CLI, until the release of .NET.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Other implementations for parts of the framework exist.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Although the runtime engine is described by an ECMA-ISO specification, other implementations of it may be encumbered by patent issues; ISO standards may include the disclaimer, "Attention is drawn to the possibility that some of the elements of this document may be the subject of patent rights.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] ISO shall not be held responsible for identifying any or all such patent rights." It is harder to develop alternatives to FCL, which is not described by an open standard and may be subject to copyright restrictions.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Also, parts of FCL have Windows-specific functions and behavior, so implementation on non-Windows platforms can be problematic.
[src:dotnet-clr/net-framework] Some alternative implementations of parts of the framework are listed here.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:dotnet-clr/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:dotnet-clr/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:dotnet-clr/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:dotnet-clr/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:dotnet-clr/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
